Application: Help Desk Ticket Tracker
  Description: Track support tickets from submission to resolution

--- Identity ---

Users authenticate with stub
Scopes are "view tickets", "create tickets", "manage tickets", and "admin tickets"

--- Roles ---

A "customer" has "view tickets" and "create tickets"
A "support agent" has "view tickets", "create tickets", and "manage tickets"
A "support manager" has "view tickets", "create tickets", "manage tickets", and "admin tickets"

--- Content ---

Content called "tickets":
  Each ticket has a title which is text, required
  Each ticket has a description which is text, required
  Each ticket has a priority which is one of: "low", "medium", "high", "critical"
  Each ticket has a category which is one of: "bug", "feature request", "question", "account issue"
  Each ticket has a submitted by which is text, required, defaults to [User.Name]
  Each ticket has an assigned to which is text
  Each ticket has a created at which is automatic, defaults to [now]
  Anyone with "view tickets" can view tickets
  Anyone with "create tickets" can create tickets
  Anyone with "manage tickets" can update tickets
  Anyone with "admin tickets" can delete tickets

Content called "comments":
  Each comment has a ticket which references tickets, required
  Each comment has an author which is text, required, defaults to [User.Name]
  Each comment has a body which is text, required
  Each comment has a posted at which is automatic, defaults to [now]
  Anyone with "view tickets" can view comments
  Anyone with "create tickets" can create comments

--- State ---

State for tickets called "ticket lifecycle":
  A ticket starts as "open"
  A ticket can also be "in progress", "waiting on customer", "resolved", or "closed"
  An open ticket can become in progress if the user has "manage tickets"
  An in progress ticket can become waiting on customer if the user has "manage tickets"
  A waiting on customer ticket can become in progress if the user has "create tickets"
  An in progress ticket can become resolved if the user has "manage tickets"
  A resolved ticket can become closed if the user has "admin tickets"
  A resolved ticket can become in progress if the user has "create tickets"

--- User Stories ---

As a customer, I want to submit a support ticket
  so that I can get help with my issue:
    Show a page called "Submit Ticket"
    Accept input for title, description, priority, and category
    Create the ticket as open

As a support agent, I want to see all open tickets
  so that I can work on resolving them:
    Show a page called "Ticket Queue"
    Display a table of tickets with columns: title, priority, category, status, assigned to, created at
    Highlight rows where [priority == "critical" || priority == "high"]
    Allow filtering by status, priority, and category
    Allow searching by title or description
    This table subscribes to tickets changes

As a support manager, I want to see ticket metrics
  so that I can monitor team performance:
    Show a page called "Support Dashboard"
    Display total ticket count with open vs resolved breakdown
    Display total comment count

--- Navigation ---

Navigation bar:
  "Queue" links to "Ticket Queue" visible to agent, manager
  "Submit" links to "Submit Ticket" visible to all
  "Dashboard" links to "Support Dashboard" visible to manager

--- API ---

Expose a REST API at /api/v1:
  GET    /tickets              lists tickets
  POST   /tickets              creates a ticket
  GET    /tickets/{id}         gets a ticket
  PUT    /tickets/{id}         updates a ticket
  DELETE /tickets/{id}         deletes a ticket
  POST   /tickets/{id}/start          transitions to in progress
  POST   /tickets/{id}/wait           transitions to waiting on customer
  POST   /tickets/{id}/resolve        transitions to resolved
  POST   /tickets/{id}/close          transitions to closed
  POST   /tickets/{id}/reopen         transitions to in progress
  GET    /comments             lists comments
  POST   /comments             creates a comment

Stream ticket updates at /api/v1/stream
